  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "My boyfriend cheated on me. I felt betrayed and it still haunts me. How to stop thinking about it?",
  "response": "I'm truly sorry you're experiencing this pain. Being betrayed by someone you love is incredibly difficult, and it's completely normal to feel hurt and haunted by these emotions. Here are some steps that might help you navigate through this challenging time:\n\n1. **Acknowledge Your Feelings**: Allow yourself to feel whatever emotions come up\u2014anger, sadness, confusion. Suppressing these feelings can prolong your healing process.\n\n2. **Seek Support**: Talk to trusted friends or family members about what you're going through. Sometimes, sharing your feelings with someone who cares can provide relief and new perspectives.\n\n3. **Consider Professional Help**: A therapist or counselor can offer strategies to cope with your emotions and help you work through feelings of betrayal and hurt.\n\n4. **Focus on Self-Care**:\n   - **Physical Health**: Engage in regular exercise, maintain a balanced diet, and ensure you're getting enough sleep.\n   - **Mental Health**: Practice mindfulness, meditation, or relaxation techniques to help manage stress and anxiety.\n   - **Hobbies and Interests**: Engage in activities you enjoy or try something new to shift your focus and bring positivity into your life.\n\n5. **Set Boundaries**: If possible, limit or eliminate contact with your ex-boyfriend, especially in the early stages of healing. This can help prevent reopening wounds and give you space to recover.\n\n6. **Reflect and Learn**: Take time to understand what happened and how it affects you. This isn't about placing blame on yourself but about understanding your needs and desires for future relationships.\n\n7. **Give Yourself Time**: Healing is a process, and it's important to be patient with yourself. It's okay to have good days and bad days as you work through your emotions.\n\n8. **Avoid Negative Coping Mechanisms**: While it might be tempting to numb the pain through distractions like excessive screen time, overeating, or other unhealthy habits, these can make things worse in the long run.\n\n9. **Stay Connected**: Maintain your social connections and don't isolate yourself. Being around supportive people can help you feel less alone.\n\n10. **Consider Forgiveness When Ready**: Forgiveness doesn't mean forgetting or condoning the hurtful behavior, but it can be a way to release the burden you carry and move forward.\n\nRemember, everyone's healing journey is unique, and it's okay to seek help along the way. You're not alone, and with time and support, you can find peace and happiness again.",
